04031nam a22005295i 9780226206363DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014021594  a97802262063637 a10.7208/97802262063632doi  a(DE-B1597)550236  a(OCoLC)897907270  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aDS61.85b.M37 2015 7aHIS0000002bisacsh  aBE 8660qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/10808:1 aMassad, Joseph A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIslam in Liberalism /cJoseph A. Massad. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Democracy Offensive and the Defenses of “Islam” -- t2 Women and/in “Islam”: The Rescue Mission of Western Liberal Feminism -- t3 Pre-Positional Conjunctions: Sexuality and/in “Islam” -- t4 Psychoanalysis, “Islam,” and the Other of Liberalism -- t5 Forget Semitism! -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the popular imagination, Islam is often associated with words like oppression, totalitarianism, intolerance, cruelty, misogyny, and homophobia, while its presumed antonyms are Christianity, the West, liberalism, individualism, freedom, citizenship, and democracy. In the most alarmist views, the West’s most cherished values—freedom, equality, and tolerance—are said to be endangered by Islam worldwide. Joseph Massad’s Islam in Liberalism explores what Islam has become in today’s world, with full attention to the multiplication of its meanings and interpretations. He seeks to understand how anxieties about tyranny, intolerance, misogyny, and homophobia, seen in the politics of the Middle East, are projected onto Islam itself. Massad shows that through this projection Europe emerges as democratic and tolerant, feminist, and pro-LGBT rights—or, in short, Islam-free. Massad documents the Christian and liberal idea that we should missionize democracy, women’s rights, sexual rights, tolerance, equality, and even therapies to cure Muslims of their un-European, un-Christian, and illiberal ways. Along the way he sheds light on a variety of controversial topics, including the meanings of democracy—and the ideological assumption that Islam is not compatible with it while Christianity is—women in Islam, sexuality and sexual freedom, and the idea of Abrahamic religions valorizing an interfaith agenda. Islam in Liberalism is an unflinching critique of Western assumptions and of the liberalism that Europe and Euro-America blindly present as a type of salvation to an assumingly unenlightened Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEast and West. 0aIslamxRelations. 0aLiberalismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aOrientalism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226206363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226206363.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles